iteration: 2
analysis:
  per_query:
    Q1:
      current_time_ms: 59
      status: pass
      bottleneck: None - already beating DuckDB (84ms)
      root_cause: Parallel hash aggregation with zone maps is working optimally. Only minor floating-point precision differences (acceptable).
    Q3:
      current_time_ms: 1203.08
      status: pass
      bottleneck: Join execution and hash table performance - 15x slower than DuckDB (80ms target)
      root_cause: "Multiple issues: (1) std::unordered_map is 3-5x slower than specialized hash tables (Robin Hood/Swiss Tables), (2) hash tables not pre-sized causing rehashing, (3) customer filter scan is sequential instead of parallel (wasting 63 of 64 cores), (4) shared filtered_orders map causes cache-line contention during parallel lineitem probe. Zone maps are working but hash join implementation is suboptimal."
    Q6:
      current_time_ms: 145.369
      status: pass
      bottleneck: Insufficient SIMD utilization - 7.6x slower than DuckDB (19ms target)
      root_cause: "Zone maps are pruning blocks correctly, but the filter loop is not fully SIMD-optimized. The code relies on compiler auto-vectorization (which is limited for mixed int32/double predicates). Manual AVX2 SIMD for date range filtering would achieve 4-6x speedup on the 64-core system. Current implementation wastes SIMD potential."
  overall: "Iteration 1 successfully implemented zone maps and parallel execution. Q1 is optimal (beating DuckDB). Critical bottleneck is Q3 (15x gap) due to inefficient hash tables and sequential customer scan. Q6 has 7.6x gap due to insufficient SIMD. Hardware: 64 cores (32 physical, 2 threads/core) with AVX2 - must exploit parallelism and SIMD to close gaps."
critical_fixes[0]:
performance_optimizations[6]{priority,target,bottleneck_category,operator,technique,description,expected_improvement,risk,requires_reingest}:
  1,Q3,cpu_bound,join,Compact Hash Tables (abseil/folly flat_hash_map),"Replace std::unordered_map with abseil::flat_hash_map or custom Robin Hood hash table in Q3 for filtered_customers (set) and filtered_orders (map). std::unordered_map has 40-60 byte overhead per entry and poor cache locality. flat_hash_map uses open addressing with SIMD-accelerated probing (SSE2 Group SWAR), achieving 3-5x faster lookups. Specifically: (1) Replace std::unordered_set<int32_t> filtered_customers with abseil::flat_hash_set<int32_t>, (2) Replace std::unordered_map<int32_t, OrderInfo> filtered_orders with abseil::flat_hash_map<int32_t, OrderInfo>. Reserve capacity: filtered_customers.reserve(c_size / 5) and filtered_orders.reserve(o_size / 15) to avoid rehashing. This optimization targets the 60M probe lookups in the lineitem loop where cache misses dominate (current: ~15-20 cycles per lookup, target: ~5-8 cycles).","3-5x speedup on Q3 join operations. Current Q3: 1203ms, expected after optimization: 300-400ms. This is the single highest-impact optimization - hash table lookups are the dominant cost in Q3's three-way join. abseil::flat_hash_map is header-only and trivial to integrate (just add absl/ directory and include <absl/container/flat_hash_map.h>).",low,false
  2,Q3,cpu_bound,scan,Parallel Scan for Customer Filter,"The customer scan in Q3 (line 108-114 in q3.cpp) is currently sequential using gendb::operators::sequential_scan. This wastes 63 of 64 cores on a 64-core system. Replace with parallel scan using the existing parallel pattern (atomic block counter + multiple threads). Specifically: (1) Use std::atomic<size_t> next_idx(0) with 64 threads, (2) Each thread processes customer rows in chunks of 1024 (cache-friendly), (3) Each thread inserts into a thread-local std::unordered_set<int32_t>, (4) Merge thread-local sets into filtered_customers. The customer filter (c_mktsegment == building_code) is trivially parallel with no dependencies. Current implementation: 1 thread on 150K rows (~1-2ms). Parallel: 64 threads (~0.03ms). This is a minor optimization (1-2ms gain) but demonstrates proper multi-core utilization and prepares the codebase for larger scale factors where customer table grows.","1-2ms speedup on Q3 (minor but demonstrates correct parallelism). More importantly, improves scalability for larger datasets (SF100+). Low-hanging fruit - easy to implement with existing parallel patterns in codebase (see Q6 atomic block counter pattern).",low,false
  3,Q6,cpu_bound,filter,Manual AVX2 SIMD for Date Range Filtering,"Q6's inner loop (lines 106-117 in q6.cpp) currently relies on compiler auto-vectorization for 4 predicates. Implement manual AVX2 SIMD for the date range check (most selective filter). Algorithm: (1) Load 8 int32_t shipdates using _mm256_loadu_si256, (2) Compare against date_start and date_end using _mm256_cmpgt_epi32, (3) Generate selection bitmask using _mm256_movemask_epi8, (4) For matching rows (bitmask bits set), check discount/quantity predicates (still scalar), (5) Accumulate revenue using _mm256_fmadd_pd (fused multiply-add for extendedprice * discount). Process 8 rows per iteration instead of 1. The key insight: date filtering is the most selective predicate (filters ~95% of rows), so SIMD-accelerating it provides maximum benefit. Discount/quantity checks can remain scalar on the ~5% of rows that pass date filter. Expected throughput: 8 rows per 3-4 cycles (SIMD) vs. 1 row per 3-4 cycles (scalar) = ~6-8x speedup on the filtering bottleneck.","4-6x speedup on Q6. Current: 145ms, expected: 25-35ms (approaching DuckDB's 19ms). The gap from 25-35ms to 19ms is likely DuckDB's additional optimizations (branchless selection, prefetching). This optimization exploits the 64-core system's AVX2 units (2 per core = 128 SIMD execution units total). Note: SF10 lineitem is 60M rows, processing in ~65K blocks = 915 blocks. With 64 threads, each thread processes ~14 blocks. SIMD on 8-row vectors means ~112K iterations per thread (down from ~900K scalar iterations).",medium,false
  4,Q3,cpu_bound,join,Hash Table Pre-sizing to Avoid Rehashing,"In Q3, the filtered_customers and filtered_orders hash tables are not pre-sized, causing expensive rehashing as they grow. Add .reserve() calls based on cardinality estimates from workload analysis. Specifically: (1) filtered_customers: 150K customers * 20% (c_mktsegment selectivity) = 30K entries → reserve 40K (1.3x headroom), (2) filtered_orders: ~100K entries based on customer join selectivity → reserve 130K. Pre-sizing eliminates O(n) rehashing operations during the build phase. std::unordered_map/set default load factor is 1.0 but performance degrades above 0.75, so reserve at 1.3x expected size. This is a standard database hash join optimization (see knowledge/joins/hash-join-variants.md line 16). Current: 3-5 rehashes during build (each copies entire table). After: zero rehashes. Savings: ~50-100ms on Q3 (5-8% of total time). Note: This optimization compounds with priority 1 (compact hash tables) - abseil::flat_hash_map benefits even more from pre-sizing due to open addressing.",50-100ms speedup on Q3 (5-8% gain). Small but easy to implement (2 lines of code). Reduces memory allocations and cache pollution. Compounds with priority 1 optimization.,low,false
  5,Q1,algorithm,aggregation,Array-Based Aggregation for Low Cardinality,"Q1 groups by (l_returnflag, l_linestatus) with only 4-6 distinct groups (workload analysis line 73). Current implementation uses hash aggregation (std::unordered_map). Replace with direct-mapped array: uint16_t key = (returnflag << 8) | linestatus → array[key]. This eliminates hash computation (2-3 cycles) and collision handling. Array-based aggregation: O(1) access with no overhead. Hash aggregation: O(1) average but 10-15 cycles per lookup due to hash function + probe. Expected savings: ~10-15ms on Q1. Implementation: (1) Create Q1Agg agg_array[256] (256 bytes, fits in L1 cache), (2) In aggregation loop: size_t idx = (returnflag << 8) | linestatus; agg_array[idx].update(...), (3) After aggregation, iterate array to extract non-empty groups. Note: Q1 is already beating DuckDB (59ms vs 84ms), so this is a minor optimization. Diminishing returns - only pursue if time permits.",10-15ms speedup on Q1 (current 59ms → 44-49ms). Minor gain since Q1 is already optimal. Low priority - only implement if other optimizations succeed and we want to push Q1 even faster.,low,false
  6,Q6,io_bound,io,Column Prefetching with madvise WILLNEED,"Q6 mmaps 4 columns (l_shipdate, l_discount, l_quantity, l_extendedprice). Current implementation likely uses default madvise (NORMAL or SEQUENTIAL). Add explicit madvise(MADV_WILLNEED) after mmap to prefetch hot columns into page cache before processing starts. This overlaps I/O latency with zone map construction. Specifically: after mmap_column calls in q6.cpp (lines 30-33), add: madvise(l_shipdate, size * sizeof(int32_t), MADV_WILLNEED) for all 4 columns. On HDD (storage design line 546: disk_type = hdd), this prefetching can save 50-100ms by initiating sequential reads early. On SSD, benefit is smaller (10-20ms). Since lineitem is sorted by l_shipdate, sequential access patterns are optimal for HDD. Prefetching ensures data is ready when parallel threads start processing blocks. Note: This optimization is orthogonal to SIMD (priority 3) - both should be applied together.","50-100ms speedup on Q6 on HDD, 10-20ms on SSD. Current: 145ms, expected with prefetching: 95-125ms (HDD). This optimization helps cold-cache scenarios (first query run). Subsequent runs benefit from OS page cache. Combined with SIMD (priority 3), Q6 could reach 20-30ms range.",low,false
storage_changes[0]:
summary: "Iteration 1 implemented zone maps and parallelism successfully - Q1 is beating DuckDB. Focus iteration 2 on Q3 (15x gap) and Q6 (7.6x gap). Top priorities: (1) Replace std::unordered_map with abseil::flat_hash_map in Q3 (3-5x join speedup), (2) Parallelize customer scan in Q3 (1-2ms gain, demonstrates proper multi-core usage), (3) Add manual AVX2 SIMD to Q6 (4-6x filter speedup). These optimizations exploit the 64-core AVX2 hardware and target the actual bottlenecks (hash lookups, SIMD underutilization). Expected post-iteration-2 performance: Q1 ~59ms (no change, already optimal), Q3 ~300-400ms (3-4x speedup, closing gap with DuckDB's 80ms), Q6 ~25-35ms (4-6x speedup, approaching DuckDB's 19ms). All optimizations are low-risk code changes, no re-ingestion required."